From Peter Hansen pgmoffc Subject Re SIMM vs DRAM In article Arthur Greene writes Can anyone tell me what the difference is between a DRAM chip and a SIMM I need the former I think to add memory to my Laserwriter Someone is offering to sell me SIMMS he removed from an SE but I have a feeling this may not be the correct form of The sockets in the Laserwriter look like they want the spidery shaped chips there are sockets each with as I recall pins arranged in two rows of Believe it or not I've never actually seen a Help A DRAM chip is a kilobit chip whereas a SIMM is a kilobyte memory The SIMM is a PCB with a pin connector edge and on the SIMM are kilobit DRAM chips making the total memory You are correct assuming that SIMMs will not fit into a Apple printers either require pin SIMMs like those in the Mac IIfx or special memory Contact your Apple dealer to find out exactly what kind of chips you Peter Hansen Bell Northern Research pgmoffc